'''Louis André Ernest Cloquet''' (born 11 October 1818, [[Paris]]; died 1855, [[Tehran]]) was a [[physician]] in [[Qajar dynasty|Qajar Iran]] of [[French people|French]] origin during the reigns of [[Mohammad Shah Qajar]] (1834–1848) and [[Naser al-Din Shah Qajar]] (1848–1896). He also served as the French minister to the court at Tehran from 1846 to 1855.

==Biography==
Cloquet the son of the noted French anatomist [[Hippolyte Cloquet]], and he also chose to become an anatomist. He was the nephew of another noted French physician, [[Jules Germain Cloquet]].{{sfn|Fisher|Avery|Hambly|Melville|1991|page=586}} From 1840 Ernest worked at various clinical offices in Paris, and was a regular contributor to the ''Société anatomique''.{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}} In 1846, with his [[thesis]] named ''De l’hématocèle vaginale'', he was awarded his doctors degree in [[medicine]], and later that year he was attached to the French mission in Tehran.{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}} He was appointed ambassador to the court and became the personal physician of the king (''[[shah]]''), succeeding another Frenchman named Dr. Labat.{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}} His regular attendance during the last illness of the then incumbent King Mohammad Shah Qajar earned him a good professional reputation.{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}} Not long after Naser al-Din Shah Qajar's ascension to the throne, Cloquet was officially re-confirmed by the King in his functions.{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}} He was also appointed as an instructor in the newly founded [[Dar ul-Funun (Persia)|Dār al-Fonūn]] University.{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}}

Following a failed attempt on the King's life in 1852 by followers of the [[Báb]], Cloquet treated him and removed a bullet from one of his wounds.{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}} When subsequently many followers of the Bab were arrested and executed, high-ranking officials at the king's court were formally invited to show their loyalty by personally participating in the executions; Cloquet did not participate, stating that it would violate his [[Hippocratic oath]].{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}}

He carried out a programme of research on [[cholera]]. Cloquet himself witnessed two outbreaks{{snd}}in 1846 and 1853.{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}} He made observations regarding the sanitary conditions of the nation as well as its climate. For his contribution to French diplomacy in Persia he received an officer's cross of the [[légion d’honneur]].{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}} An anecdote is told of when in 1855 his native assistant mistakenly poured him a glass of tincture of cantharides (also known as [[Spanish fly]]) instead of [[brandy]]; when Cloquet realized what had happened, he drank another glass after it in order to reduce the length of his suffering.{{sfn|Richter-Bernburg|1992|page=718}} Cloquet was succeeded as the king's personal physician by [[Jakob Eduard Polak]] in 1856.{{sfn|Gurney|Nabavi|1993|pages=662–668}}

